COMMENTS AND WHITESPACE

    ` Backtick starts a comment, ends at the line break.

    Whitespace and commas are interchangeable separators. These are the same:

        add 1 2
        add 1, 2


LITERALS

    ` Booleans
    yes
    no

    ` Nil
    none

    ` Integers
    42
    -7

    ` Reals
    3.14
    1.5e10

    ` Strings (single or double quotes, backslash escapes)
    "hello, world"
    'it\'s fine'


VARIABLES

    ` Assign with =
    x = 42
    name = "Plain"

    ` Read a variable by using its name as an argument
    print x
    print name


EXPRESSIONS

    ` Wrap any statement in [...] to use its result as a value
    print [add 1 2]
    print [concat "Hello, " name "!"]
    x = [multiply 6 7]


ARITHMETIC

    ` Prefix form
    print [add 10 3]         ` 13
    print [subtract 10 3]    ` 7
    print [multiply 10 3]    ` 30
    print [divide 10 3]      ` 3
    print [modulo 10 3]      ` 1

    ` Infix form
    x = 10
    print [x + 3]            ` 13
    print [x - 3]            ` 7
    print [x * 3]            ` 30
    print [x / 3]            ` 3
    print [x % 3]            ` 1

    ` Reals promote automatically
    print [add 1 0.5]        ` 1.5
    print [x + 0.5]          ` 10.5


COMPARISON

    ` Prefix form
    print [equal 1 1]        ` yes
    print [less 1 2]         ` yes
    print [greater 3 2]      ` yes

    ` Infix form — all six operators
    x = 5
    print [x = 5]            ` yes   (= means equality inside [...])
    print [x != 4]           ` yes
    print [x < 10]           ` yes
    print [x > 3]            ` yes
    print [x <= 5]           ` yes
    print [x >= 5]           ` yes

    ` Works on strings too
    print [equal "a" "a"]    ` yes
    print ["a" < "b"]        ` yes


LOGIC

    print [not yes]              ` no

    ` Prefix form
    print [and yes yes]          ` yes
    print [or no yes]            ` yes

    ` Infix form
    x = 5
    print [x > 0 and x < 10]    ` yes
    print [x < 0 or x > 3]      ` yes


STRINGS

    print [concat "Hello, " "world" "!"]    ` Hello, world!

    ` Numbers are coerced to strings
    print [concat "Result: " [add 1 2]]     ` Result: 3


BLOCKS

    ` Curly braces create a deferred block — not evaluated until needed
    { print "I run when called" }

    ` Colon shorthand: opens a block, semicolon closes it
    : print "same thing" ;


IF / ELSE

    x = 10

    if [x > 5] {
        print "big"
    }

    ` With else
    if [x < 0] {
        print "negative"
    } {
        print "non-negative"
    }

    ` Colon shorthand (no else)
    if [x = 10]: print "exactly ten" ;


REPEAT

    ` Infinite loop — use break to exit
    x = 0
    repeat {
        x = [x + 1]
        if [x = 3]: break ;
    }
    print x    ` 3

    ` Counted loop
    repeat 5 {
        print "hello"
    }

    ` Conditional loop (like while)
    i = 0
    repeat { [i < 5] } {
        print i
        i = [i + 1]
    }


BREAK

    ` Break exits the nearest repeat
    i = 0
    repeat {
        if [i = 3]: break ;
        print i
        i = [i + 1]
    }
    ` Prints: 0, 1, 2


FUNCTIONS (immutable, named)

    ` Declare with function keyword: name {parameters} {body}
    function double {n} {
        return [multiply n 2]
    }

    print [double 7]    ` 14

    ` Inline assignment form — identical result 
    double = function {n} { return [multiply n 2] }

    ` Functions cannot be reassigned (immutable binding)


PROCEDURES (mutable, named)

    ` Declare with procedure: name {parameters} {body}
    ` Procedures are reassignable; typically used for side effects.
    procedure greet {name} {
        print [concat "Hello, " name "!"]
    }

    greet "world"    ` Hello, world!

    ` Inline assignment form
    greet = procedure {name} { print [concat "Hi, " name "!"] }

    ` Can be reassigned later
    greet = procedure {name} { print [concat "Hey, " name "."] }
    greet "Plain"    ` Hey, Plain.


RETURN

    function clamp {value minimum maximum} {
        if [value < minimum]: return minimum ;
        if [value > maximum]: return maximum ;
        return value
    }

    print [clamp 5 0 10]     ` 5
    print [clamp -3 0 10]    ` 0
    print [clamp 99 0 10]    ` 10


NESTED EXPRESSIONS

    ` Expressions can nest freely
    function square {n} { return [n * n] }

    print [square 3 + square 4]    ` prefix add still works: [add [square 3] [square 4]] = 25
    print [[square 3] + [square 4]]    ` infix: 25

    ` Fibonacci
    function fibonacci {n} {
        if [n < 2]: return n ;
        return [[fibonacci [n - 1]] + [fibonacci [n - 2]]]
    }

    print [fibonacci 10]    ` 55


MULTIPLE STATEMENTS

    ` Semicolons separate statements on one line
    a = 1; b = 2; print [add a b]    ` 3


FIRST-CLASS COMMANDS

    ` Built-in commands are regular callable bindings in the frame.
    ` They can be stored in variables and passed as arguments just like
    ` any user-defined function.

    ` Store a built-in in a variable
    branch = if
    branch [2 > 1] { print "yes" } { print "no" }    ` yes

    ` Pass a callable as an argument
    function apply {operation a b} {
        return [operation a b]
    }

    print [apply add 3 4]         ` 7
    print [apply multiply 3 4]    ` 12

    ` Works with any user-defined callable too
    function double {n} { return [n * 2] }
    function triple {n} { return [n * 3] }

    transform = double
    print [apply transform 5]    ` 10

    transform = triple
    print [apply transform 5]    ` 15

    ` Higher-order: a function that applies another function twice
    function twice {f x} {
        return [f [f x]]
    }

    print [twice double 3]    ` 12  (3 * 2 * 2)

    ` Override a built-in — no keywords are reserved
    add = function {a b} { return [a + b + 1] }   ` biased add
    print [add 2 3]    ` 6

    ` Restore by redefining
    add = procedure {a b} { return [a + b] }
    print [add 2 3]    ` 5
